The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 World Bank injects $3.8bn 

 New Delhi, June 3 (PTI): The World Banks lending to India will touch $3.8 billion in the year ending June 30, making the country the largest borrower from the multilateral financial institution.

 World Banks involvement with India has increased tremendously and the $3.8 billion to be extended till June 30 is the largest amount extended so far, World Bank executive director Dhanendra Kumar said.

 Of the $3.8 billion, $2.32 billion will be zero interest grants and credit provided by the banks International Development Association, Kumar said. The banks lending to India was $1.4 billion last year.

 He said half of the $3.8 billion would be deployed for development projects in rural areas. The bank is also expected to approve 14 projects by the end of June and would provide additional assistance for two projects already undertaken, he said.




